# Browser Testing — Mistakes to Avoid

## 1. Clear Vite cache after installing packages

After `npm install` of new packages, the dev server will crash with 500 / 504 errors.
Always do this before restarting:

```bash
rm -rf node_modules/.vite
```

## 2. Flush server cache after changing decode/render logic

Content fetched from GitHub is cached in memory (or Redis). If you fix how content is decoded or rendered, the old broken result is still cached. Flush it:

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5173/api/webhook -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"ref":"refs/heads/github"}'
```

Don't waste tool calls debugging "why didn't my fix work" — it's the cache.

## 3. httpOnly cookies can't be set via JavaScript

The `gh_token` cookie is `httpOnly: true`. You cannot set it with `document.cookie` or `javascript:` URLs. Use the server-side dev endpoint instead:

```
GET /api/auth/dev-token?token=<GITHUB_PAT>
```

Then navigate to any URL with `#token=<PAT>` and hard-reload to also populate localStorage (needed for Edit/Drafts buttons in the Header).

The test PAT is stored in `.env` as `GITHUB_TEST_PAT`. Read it from there — never hardcode it.

## 4. The Edit button only appears on content pages

Don't navigate to `/` and expect to see the Edit button. The home page has no `sourcePath`. Navigate to a wiki content page like `/chapters/...` to test editing.
